shows the estimated familywise error rate (FWER), defined as the
probability of at least one false positive across m tests, as a function
of the number of tests (m), based on 10,000 replications under the
global null (\(\theta = 0\) for all tests). The red curve corresponds to
declaring at least one discovery when at least one two-sided one-sample
z-test p-value \textless{} 0.05, whereas the blue curve corresponds to
declaring at least one discovery when at least one pd \textgreater{}
0.975 under the conjugate normal Bayesian model. Rows vary the per-test
sample size (\(n = 30, 50, 100\)), and columns vary the prior scale
(\(\theta \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \tau^2)\) with
